Saburo's relationship with his father is quite detached, initially. When Saburo introduces the fact that he is going to run eight hundred meters, a short-distance event, his father merely answers with "eight hundred meters? Is that all?". However, his father expresses recognition towards Saburo's goals when he states "'I'll be taking you out to Kaigane Station to clock your runs". The first time his father displays interest and a willingness to assist in Saburo's sport, sparks appreciation in Saburo, however, he questions it as his father is "old" and "an academic". Although their rides to the station are "awkward and silent", it is not until they reach their destination where Saburo feels "complete harmony between them". Saburo and his father's diversities are woven into one when they finally discover a mutality to bond over. Combined with the efforts of both father and son, they become able-bodied in establishing a comforting peace and calming nature between the two of them. When Saburo grows older and is introduced to the land of academics, he finds their conversations are "no longer awkward", and he learns to appreciate his father's perspective and the diverse aspects to him he had never known. The mutual efforts on behalf of the two of them to not only understand one another, but to actively involve themselves in one another's passions, grants access to the healthy and wholesome relationship that truly emerges in Saburo's later life.
